.1883) to Women2Win (est.2005), the party has exploited women’s political commitment and their social power from the grass-roots to the heights of the establishment. Yet, although it is the party that extended the equal franchise, had the first woman MP to sit Parliament, and produced the first two women Prime Ministers, the UK Conservative Party has developed political roles for women that jar with feminist and progressive agendas. Conservative women have tended to be more concerned about the fulfilment of women’s duties than the realisation of women’s rights. This book tackles the ambivalences between women’s politicisation and women’s emancipation in the history of Britain’s most electorally successful and hegemonic political party.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh  aBritish conservatism.  aChristabel Pankhurst.  aConservative Century.  aConservative Party.  aConservative women.  aEdwardian Britain.  aLady Iveagh.  aNational Union of Conservative Associations.  aPrimrose League.  aTory Party.  aWomen's Social and Political Union.  across-class language.  acultural dominance.  aelectoral culture.  afemale conservatism.  afemale unionism.  agender inclusive approach.  apolitical machinations.  apolitics of gender.  asuffrage organization.1 aBeers, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerthezène, Clarisse, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerthezène, Clarisse, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBingham, Adrian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Rosie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChilds, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat